'''Thomas William "Tom" Shales'''<ref name=ref1>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/14/Tom-Shales.html Filmreference.com]</ref> (born November 3, 1944) is an [[United States|American]] critic of television programming and operations. He is best known as [[critic|TV critic]] for ''[[The Washington Post]]''; in 1988, Shales received the [[Pulitzer Prize]]. He also writes a column for the television news trade publication ''NewsPro'', published by Crain Communications.

==Life and career==
Shales was born in [[Elgin, Illinois|Elgin]], [[Illinois]], the son of Hulda Louise (née Reko) and Clyde LeRoy Shales.<ref name=ref1/>  Shales's first professional job was with radio station WRMN, in Elgin at the age of 18. He served on the station's disc jockey, local news reporter, writer and announcer, on both the AM and FM bands. He later worked with [[Voice of America]] as a producer of broadcasts to the Far East.<ref name="The Washington Post Writers Group"/>

Shales graduated from [[American University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], where he was Editor-In-Chief of the student newspaper, ''The Eagle'', for the 1966-1967 academic year,<ref>[http://www.library.american.edu/about/archives/eagle_history.html American University Library - History of The Eagle<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> as well as the paper's movie critic.<ref name="The Washington Post Writers Group">[http://www.postwritersgroup.com/shales.htm The Washington Post Writers Group<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Shales worked as Entertainment Editor at the ''[[Washington Examiner]]'' from 1968 to 1971.<ref>{{IMDb name|1143576|section=bio}}</ref> He joined the ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' as a writer in the Style section in 1972, was named chief television critic in July 1977, and was appointed TV Editor in June 1979. The Washington Post Writers Group syndicated his column since 1979.<ref name="The Washington Post Writers Group"/> Shales wrote for the ''Washington Post'' for several decades, but left the paper effective December 31, 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tom-shales-confirms-he-will-32124|title=Tom Shales Confirms He Will Leave Washington Post after 39 Years|author=Bryan Alexander|publisher=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 22, 2010}}</ref>

During 1998–1999, Shales was a frequent film critic for ''[[Morning Edition]]'' on [[National Public Radio]].<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/author-708/ Tom Shales - Rotten Tomatoes<!-- Bot generated title -->], [[Rotten Tomatoes]]</ref> He was twice a guest co-host on the television show ''[[At the Movies with Ebert & Roeper|Roger Ebert & the Movies]]'' after the death of [[Gene Siskel]].<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1143576/maindetails Tom Shales<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Shales was a member of the [[Peabody Award|Peabody Awards]] Board of Jurors from 1991 to 1996.<ref>http://www.peabodyawards.com/stories/story/george-foster-peabody-awards-board-members</ref>

==Honors==
Shales received the [[Pulitzer Prize|Pulitzer Prize for Criticism]] in 1988, for his work at ''[[Washington Post]]''.<ref>[http://www.postwritersgroup.com/shales.htm Postwritersgroup.com]</ref>

